I'm an Iranian-American
peace and human rights

01:45:44.350 --> 01:45:47.560
and environmental
activist, and I'm

01:45:47.560 --> 01:45:51.650
a participant in
Iran's Green Movement,

01:45:51.650 --> 01:45:58.430
a supporter of the Arab Spring
Movements against dictatorship.

01:45:58.430 --> 01:46:02.730
And obviously I'm a
passionate participant

01:46:02.730 --> 01:46:06.910
in the Occupy Movement
in this country, which

01:46:06.910 --> 01:46:12.170
I believe has already
awakened incredible energy,

01:46:12.170 --> 01:46:20.140
and therefore I am
hopeful, but also fearful

01:46:20.140 --> 01:46:28.320
of what it may do wrong
in order to possibly waste

01:46:28.320 --> 01:46:30.550
this last chance movement.

01:46:30.550 --> 01:46:35.050
So please share with
us your wisdom about

01:46:35.050 --> 01:46:38.670
what is it that you think,
at this point in history,

01:46:38.670 --> 01:46:45.770
the Occupy Movement needs to
be wary of or be careful about?

01:46:45.770 --> 01:46:48.360
Well, like you, I think
the Occupy Movement

01:46:48.360 --> 01:46:51.310
has been quite a
remarkable success, way

01:46:51.310 --> 01:46:53.440
beyond what I thought.

01:46:53.440 --> 01:46:59.410
And the tactic has been very
effective for a lot of reasons.

01:46:59.410 --> 01:47:03.120
One effect that it's
had is just changing

01:47:03.120 --> 01:47:05.170
kind of national discourse.

01:47:05.170 --> 01:47:07.320
In fact, even the
terminology and imagery

01:47:07.320 --> 01:47:10.890
of the Occupy Movement is
now sort of mainstream.

01:47:10.890 --> 01:47:17.090
It's focused attention on
serious problems-- inequality;

01:47:17.090 --> 01:47:20.210
like somebody asked before,
the purchase of elections;

01:47:20.210 --> 01:47:24.570
shredding of democracy;
the extraordinary power

01:47:24.570 --> 01:47:27.900
of financial institutions
which probably

01:47:27.900 --> 01:47:30.850
contribute very little, if
anything, to the economy.

01:47:30.850 --> 01:47:36.320
In fact, the most respected
financial commentator

01:47:36.320 --> 01:47:39.050
in the world, I
think, Martin Wolf

01:47:39.050 --> 01:47:43.030
of the Financial Times in
London is very conservative,

01:47:43.030 --> 01:47:45.070
highly respected correspondent.

01:47:45.070 --> 01:47:47.480
He describes the
financial institutions

01:47:47.480 --> 01:47:49.530
that have developed
in the last 30 years

01:47:49.530 --> 01:47:55.580
as kind of like a larvae that
destroys the host in which it's

01:47:55.580 --> 01:47:56.408
embedded.

01:47:56.408 --> 01:47:57.720
[LAUGHTER]

01:47:58.220 --> 01:47:59.964
[APPLAUSE]

01:48:00.840 --> 01:48:03.782
I couldn't get away with
saying that, but he can.

01:48:03.782 --> 01:48:05.240
And I can get away
with quoting it.

01:48:08.260 --> 01:48:11.230
And the Occupy Movement
has directed attention

01:48:11.230 --> 01:48:13.860
to foreclosures,
homelessness, a lot

01:48:13.860 --> 01:48:16.770
of problems that were there
but were kind of buried.

01:48:16.770 --> 01:48:20.190
Another major contribution
it's made, in my opinion,

01:48:20.190 --> 01:48:27.490
is just overcoming the
atomization of the Society.

01:48:27.490 --> 01:48:30.340
The United States is a
very atomized society.

01:48:30.340 --> 01:48:31.910
People are kind of alone.

01:48:31.910 --> 01:48:35.990
You know, the ideal social
unit, from the point

01:48:35.990 --> 01:48:41.020
of view of concentrated
power, is a dyad.

01:48:41.020 --> 01:48:44.730
You and the screen,
nothing else.

01:48:44.730 --> 01:48:47.980
That's a way to make sure
that everybody's conforming.

01:48:47.980 --> 01:48:49.425
And there's a lot of that.

01:48:49.425 --> 01:48:51.330
You know, children.

01:48:51.330 --> 01:48:55.140
It's a real disease,
a pathology.

01:48:55.140 --> 01:48:57.130
And the Occupy
Movement's overcoming it.

01:48:57.130 --> 01:49:01.100
It's creating,
spontaneously, communities

01:49:01.100 --> 01:49:06.870
of people who actually are
reviving traditional ideals.

01:49:06.870 --> 01:49:10.670
I mean, if there were any real
conservatives in the country,

01:49:10.670 --> 01:49:13.210
they'd be applauding
the fact that they're

01:49:13.210 --> 01:49:18.530
reviving the concepts of
solidarity, mutual support,

01:49:18.530 --> 01:49:21.420
sympathy, free
discussion, and so

01:49:21.420 --> 01:49:25.990
on that are just the most
traditional values we have.

01:49:25.990 --> 01:49:28.120
There's been major
efforts to destroy them,

01:49:28.120 --> 01:49:32.820
and that's being revived in the
communities of mutual support

01:49:32.820 --> 01:49:34.790
and solidarity that
are being created.

01:49:34.790 --> 01:49:37.130
Well, all of this is
really important, I think.

01:49:37.130 --> 01:49:39.570
But now, where do
you go from here?

01:49:39.570 --> 01:49:43.300
Well, first of all,
I don't regard myself

01:49:43.300 --> 01:49:46.220
as any kind of an
expert on tactics.

01:49:46.220 --> 01:49:49.580
I've been wrong so many
times on tactical judgments

01:49:49.580 --> 01:49:50.705
that I usually shut up.

01:49:55.000 --> 01:49:56.970
And these are
important judgments.

01:49:56.970 --> 01:49:58.510
Tactical judgments
are those that

01:49:58.510 --> 01:50:02.960
have direct human consequences,
so they're not marginal.

01:50:02.960 --> 01:50:07.690
But my general feeling
is that tactics

01:50:07.690 --> 01:50:10.610
have a kind of a half-life.

01:50:10.610 --> 01:50:13.440
They have diminishing returns.

01:50:13.440 --> 01:50:18.420
They may be very successful,
but it sort of declines.

01:50:18.420 --> 01:50:24.350
After a while, there's kind of
a dynamism in which the tactic

01:50:24.350 --> 01:50:28.070
begins to overcome
the purpose, apart

01:50:28.070 --> 01:50:30.610
from beginning to
alienate other people who

01:50:30.610 --> 01:50:32.370
you're trying to reach.

01:50:32.370 --> 01:50:35.150
So while I think that
the Occupy tactic has

01:50:35.150 --> 01:50:39.860
been a great success, I
think it has to be rethought,

01:50:39.860 --> 01:50:44.820
and moves have to be
made somehow to reach out

01:50:44.820 --> 01:50:46.692
into larger communities.

01:50:46.692 --> 01:50:51.650
Now, that's been going on in
a number of interesting ways.

01:50:51.650 --> 01:50:54.800
Like one of the developments
in several cities,

01:50:54.800 --> 01:50:56.880
I know in New York and
Boston and elsewhere,

01:50:56.880 --> 01:51:00.410
has been what's been
called Occupy The Hood.

01:51:00.410 --> 01:51:04.450
Neighborhood Occupy Movements,
which have, to some extent,

01:51:04.450 --> 01:51:09.730
integrated with the ones that
make the newspapers, Occupy

01:51:09.730 --> 01:51:12.700
Wall Street, occupy your
neighborhood in Brooklyn.

01:51:12.700 --> 01:51:14.790
Occupy other things.

01:51:14.790 --> 01:51:18.370
And those deal with
the immediate problems

01:51:18.370 --> 01:51:20.220
of the local people.

01:51:20.220 --> 01:51:23.684
And they can be very serious.

01:51:23.684 --> 01:51:25.100
I mean, it could
be something that

01:51:25.100 --> 01:51:29.600
sounds as simple as getting
a traffic light where

01:51:29.600 --> 01:51:31.540
kids have to cross the street.

01:51:31.540 --> 01:51:34.400
I mean, if people
can achieve that,

01:51:34.400 --> 01:51:37.460
they learn you can achieve
something by mutual aid

01:51:37.460 --> 01:51:39.390
and you can go on.

01:51:39.390 --> 01:51:42.070
That's what successful
organizing is about.

01:51:42.070 --> 01:51:46.880
And if the Occupy Movements
can go in that direction,

01:51:46.880 --> 01:51:50.660
reach out to larger
sections of the population

01:51:50.660 --> 01:51:53.680
and engage the
working class, which

01:51:53.680 --> 01:51:57.000
they have yet really to do,
and that's very significant,

01:51:57.000 --> 01:52:00.090
then I think they
have great prospects.

01:52:00.090 --> 01:52:01.660
But it's not easy to do this.

01:52:01.660 --> 01:52:05.500
And we have a lot of repression,
violent repression sometimes,

01:52:05.500 --> 01:52:09.910
and power systems don't
fade away cheerfully.

01:52:09.910 --> 01:52:13.040
They'll do what they
can to control things,

01:52:13.040 --> 01:52:16.250
but I think that David
Hume was correct--

01:52:16.250 --> 01:52:19.640
"power is in the hands
of the governed."

01:52:19.640 --> 01:52:23.880
There's nothing-- there's no
weapon that the powerful have

01:52:23.880 --> 01:52:26.090
other than control of opinion.

01:52:26.090 --> 01:52:28.880
Attitudes, opinions,
beliefs, if they

01:52:28.880 --> 01:52:34.090
can make people feel hopeless,
dependent, passive, atomized,

01:52:34.090 --> 01:52:36.000
OK, then you can keep power.

01:52:36.000 --> 01:52:39.660
But the governed,
that is the 99%

01:52:39.660 --> 01:52:44.120
in the imagery of the Occupy
Movement, they have the power.

01:52:44.120 --> 01:52:47.700
But they have to get
organized, committed.

01:52:47.700 --> 01:52:50.850
And that's the task
of people who want

01:52:50.850 --> 01:52:54.090
to devote themselves to this.

01:52:54.090 --> 01:52:56.010
[APPLAUSE]

01:53:02.270 --> 01:53:03.970
We have time for
one final question.

01:53:03.970 --> 01:53:06.560
It will come from this side.

01:53:06.560 --> 01:53:08.580
Hi, Dr. Chomsky.

01:53:08.580 --> 01:53:10.570
I met you first with
Daniel Berrigan.

01:53:10.570 --> 01:53:11.640
It's a long time ago.

01:53:11.640 --> 01:53:16.030
But anyway, getting back to
your specific expertise in

01:53:16.030 --> 01:53:18.250
linguistics.

01:53:18.250 --> 01:53:22.970
It's been troublesome to me
that the media will use words

01:53:22.970 --> 01:53:27.160
like "socialism,"
"class warfare,"

01:53:27.160 --> 01:53:30.450
but we never hear "fascism."

01:53:30.450 --> 01:53:35.870
And from my studies of ideology,
state-supported capitalism,

01:53:35.870 --> 01:53:40.690
pretty much what you've been
talking about, is fascism.

01:53:40.690 --> 01:53:43.530
I know words have power,
and you know that, too.

01:53:43.530 --> 01:53:50.230
Are we too shy to talk about
what basically almost brought

01:53:50.230 --> 01:53:53.660
the end of mankind
in the last century?

01:53:53.660 --> 01:53:56.260
Or is it just the
media controls and you

01:53:56.260 --> 01:53:59.720
have to go to Link
TV or Democracy Now

01:53:59.720 --> 01:54:01.230
or-- I don't know.

01:54:01.230 --> 01:54:04.340
But they are not supported.

01:54:04.340 --> 01:54:08.650
They have to be supported
by people donating to them.

01:54:08.650 --> 01:54:12.500
Isn't anyone aware?

01:54:12.500 --> 01:54:16.940
Well, the history of that
word is kind of interesting.

01:54:16.940 --> 01:54:22.810
Fascism obviously took on bad
connotations in the 1940s.

01:54:22.810 --> 01:54:24.677
But if you go back--
and, incidentally,

01:54:24.677 --> 01:54:26.010
the same is true of other words.

01:54:26.010 --> 01:54:27.880
Like take "propaganda."

01:54:27.880 --> 01:54:32.140
The term "propaganda" now
is not used for information.

01:54:32.140 --> 01:54:33.080
In English.

01:54:33.080 --> 01:54:35.430
It still is in other languages.

01:54:35.430 --> 01:54:39.270
If you go back to the
1920s, information

01:54:39.270 --> 01:54:41.050
was just called propaganda.

01:54:41.050 --> 01:54:43.310
Like Edward Bernays,
who I mentioned,

01:54:43.310 --> 01:54:47.170
the founder of the public
relations industry,

01:54:47.170 --> 01:54:50.420
the book of his from which
I was quoting on engineering

01:54:50.420 --> 01:54:52.870
of consent and controlling
the masses and so on

01:54:52.870 --> 01:54:54.630
is called Propaganda.

01:54:54.630 --> 01:54:56.520
Propaganda is just
what you do when

01:54:56.520 --> 01:54:58.900
you try to control
beliefs and attitudes.

01:54:58.900 --> 01:55:02.190
Well, since the
1930s and the '40s,

01:55:02.190 --> 01:55:07.530
you can't use that term anymore
for its obvious connotations.

01:55:07.530 --> 01:55:09.770
Fascism is a very
interesting one.

01:55:09.770 --> 01:55:11.360
And we can learn a
lot about ourselves

01:55:11.360 --> 01:55:14.120
from looking at its history.

01:55:14.120 --> 01:55:18.000
Before the Second World War,
before the United States

01:55:18.000 --> 01:55:22.300
got into the Second
World War, 1941,

01:55:22.300 --> 01:55:25.970
fascism was not regarded
particularly critically.

01:55:25.970 --> 01:55:28.830
In fact, there's a
very important book

01:55:28.830 --> 01:55:32.510
I urge you to read if you
haven't called Business

01:55:32.510 --> 01:55:36.750
as a System of Power, by one of
the great political economists,

01:55:36.750 --> 01:55:40.160
Robert Brady, a
Veblen economist.

01:55:40.160 --> 01:55:43.680
It's about the spread of fascism
through the industrial world.

01:55:43.680 --> 01:55:46.580
He points out that
in every country, all

01:55:46.580 --> 01:55:50.990
the industrial countries,
there are developments

01:55:50.990 --> 01:55:54.630
of basically fascist character.

01:55:54.630 --> 01:55:59.045
And he discusses them, and,
perfectly understandable,

01:55:59.045 --> 01:56:02.230
he was quite right, in fact.

01:56:02.230 --> 01:56:05.240
There's nothing inherent
in fascism that says

01:56:05.240 --> 01:56:07.170
you have to have gas chambers.

01:56:07.170 --> 01:56:10.120
That's a special
thing that developed.

01:56:10.120 --> 01:56:13.250
And in fact, say
Mussolini's fascism

01:56:13.250 --> 01:56:16.500
was very highly-regarded
in the United States.

01:56:16.500 --> 01:56:18.820
Remember, that's pre-Nazi.

01:56:18.820 --> 01:56:25.130
So FDR, Franklin Roosevelt,
President Roosevelt,

01:56:25.130 --> 01:56:30.560
he described Mussolini as "that
admirable Italian gentleman."

01:56:30.560 --> 01:56:36.780
I mean, as late as 1939 he
was praising Mussolini saying,

01:56:36.780 --> 01:56:39.400
well, he's been kind
of misled by Hitler,

01:56:39.400 --> 01:56:42.130
but basically doing
the right thing.

01:56:42.130 --> 01:56:46.030
And when fascism was
instituted in Italy,

01:56:46.030 --> 01:56:51.300
and it was pretty ugly, it
was praised across the board

01:56:51.300 --> 01:56:53.190
in the United States.

01:56:53.190 --> 01:56:55.260
Business Investment shot up.

01:56:55.260 --> 01:56:57.080
It also did after
Hitler came in.

01:56:59.880 --> 01:57:02.850
Fortune magazine, the
main business journal,

01:57:02.850 --> 01:57:06.790
had an issue in, I think, 1932.

01:57:06.790 --> 01:57:10.860
The title, you look at
the front page cover,

01:57:10.860 --> 01:57:15.580
big letters it says "The Wops
are Unwopping Themselves,"

01:57:15.580 --> 01:57:18.800
meaning the wops are finally
doing something right.

01:57:18.800 --> 01:57:22.070
You know, they've got a fascist
government, which works,

01:57:22.070 --> 01:57:23.810
and we like that.

01:57:23.810 --> 01:57:27.100
People on the left
were praising it.

01:57:27.100 --> 01:57:29.540
Same with Nazism.

01:57:29.540 --> 01:57:36.070
I mean, as late as 1938,
Roosevelt's main advisor,

01:57:36.070 --> 01:57:40.370
Sumner Welles, went to
the Munich Conference.

01:57:40.370 --> 01:57:44.430
That's the conference which
tore up Czechoslovakia.

01:57:44.430 --> 01:57:51.380
And he came back full of
praise for the Nazi moderates,

01:57:51.380 --> 01:57:56.170
who were going to help us
usher in a new era of peace.

01:57:56.170 --> 01:58:01.080
They're the moderates kind of
protecting civilized values

01:58:01.080 --> 01:58:03.820
from the extremists of the
right and left and so on.

01:58:03.820 --> 01:58:08.010
I mean, George Kennan, who's
very much honored and respected

01:58:08.010 --> 01:58:10.760
now-- there's a major
biography that just came out

01:58:10.760 --> 01:58:14.590
full of praise-- if you take
a look at his actual record,

01:58:14.590 --> 01:58:21.510
he was the American Consul
in Berlin right through 1941.

01:58:21.510 --> 01:58:24.050
He was withdrawn, Pearl Harbor.

01:58:24.050 --> 01:58:28.470
And he was sending back
diplomatic correspondence

01:58:28.470 --> 01:58:30.530
to Washington
saying, you shouldn't

01:58:30.530 --> 01:58:32.680
be so hard on the Nazis.

01:58:32.680 --> 01:58:36.597
They're doing some things
wrong, but basically we

01:58:36.597 --> 01:58:37.680
can do business with them.

01:58:37.680 --> 01:58:39.770
They're the right
kind of people.

01:58:39.770 --> 01:58:42.420
Well, a couple of years later,
you couldn't talk about fascism

01:58:42.420 --> 01:58:43.310
that way.

01:58:43.310 --> 01:58:47.690
Fascism meant crematoria, you
know, gas chambers, and so on.

01:58:47.690 --> 01:58:49.660
So you stopped using the word.

01:58:49.660 --> 01:58:51.160
But your point is correct.

01:58:51.160 --> 01:58:55.510
As a social and political
order, Robert Brady

01:58:55.510 --> 01:58:57.210
knew what he was talking about.

01:58:57.210 --> 01:59:01.310
There are elements of this
kind of state capitalist order

01:59:01.310 --> 01:59:06.000
all over the industrial
world taking different forms.

01:59:06.000 --> 01:59:06.500
Thank you.

01:59:06.500 --> 01:59:08.374
Well, thank you all for
all of your questions

01:59:08.374 --> 01:59:09.820
and for your attention.

01:59:09.820 --> 01:59:11.020
[APPLAUSE]

